Questions:¶

What makes a MVP player different and what effect do they have on becoming a champion?¶

Does playing position and style effect winning an MVP award and can we improve positions and playing style groups?¶

Can we predict MVPs based on their performance?¶

In [639]:
# Converting team abbreviations to latest team name
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["MLH","STL","TOT","TRI"], "ATL")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["BRK","NYN","NJN"], "BKN")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("CHH", "CHA")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["PHW","SFW"], "GSW")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("SDR", "HOU")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["BUF","SDC"], "LAC")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("MNL", "LAL")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("VAN", "MEM")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["NOK","NOH"], "NOP")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("SEA", "OKC")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("SYR", "PHI")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("PHO", "PHX")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["KCK","KCO","CIN","ROC"], "SAC")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace("NOJ", "UTA")
stats['Tm'] = stats['Tm'].replace(["CAP","CHP","CHZ","WSB","BAL","BLB"], "WAS")

TSA = FGA + 0.44 * FTA

(True Shooting) = (Field Goal Attempts) + 0.44 * (Free Throw Attempts)

TS% = PTS / (2 * TSA)

True Shooting Percentage = Points / 2 * (True Shooting)

Any of the variables where a percentge is calculated and is giving a null is due to the denominator of the calculation being 0. As a result these metrics will be replaced with 0. Like the example formula above.

Feature Engineering:¶

For the first feature I created a calculated a column which highlights the first year an NBA player starts in the league. The idea behind this is I could then take away the debut year from the current year and this would give me years of experience in the NBA. Which could be a useful insight into the experience of an MVP player and a Championship winning team.

The next features are going to be more about the effect a player has when on the court. Most of our variables are totals and do not reflect the true performance of a player time on the court. A result will be creating new features which will be per game.

From the 1980 season till 2017 we have had:

  • 22 different MVPs
  • Only 8 MVPs never reached a final
  • 7 MVPs have reached the final and lost, 4 of which have a 100% loss record and 3 have a win percentage ranging from 50% to 67%
  • 10 MVPs have reached the final and won, 7 of which have a 100%-win record
  • Most wins in a final is 4 by Michael Jordan at 100% win rate

From our sample dataset we can workout the probability of being a champion given MVP award has been won.

So after using a group by functions and exporting the data I used excel to calculate the below:

Bayes Theorm:¶

P(Champ|MVP) = P(MVP|CHAMP) * P(CHAMP) / P(MVP)

         = P(MVP|CHAMP) * (0.03240188) / (0.00238619)

P(MVP|CHAMP) is unknown so we can use conditional probability to calculate it using the joint probability:

P(MVP|CHAMP) = P(MVP,CHAMP) / P(CHAMP)

         = (0.00094192) / (0.03240188)

         = 0.0290699

Now we can replace back into the first formula:

P(Champ|MVP) = (0.0290699) * (0.03240188) / (0.00238619) = 0.39

So, The probability of a Player being a champion given he has won the MVP award is around 40%

Position Profiles¶

Based on analysis

“PG” – Point Guard

  • Shorter and lighter than all other positions with an average height of 189cm and weight of 85kg
  • AST - King of assists
  • STL – I can steal the ball if I must
  • TOV – I can turn things around
  • PF – I dont like to foul
  • Known as "The cool one"

“SG” – Shooting Guard

  • This group of players are taller than PGs but not necessarily always heavier with an average height of 196cm and weight of 90kg
  • PTS – I can’t miss
  • STL – I can steal the ball alright
  • Known as "The Talisman"

“SF” – Small Forward

  • Is the third tallest group of players with an average height of 202cm and weight of 104kg. due to an outlier in the MVP data in weight the average looks more in the middle of the range 90-95kg
  • PTS - I can shoot to
  • AST – I can assist to
  • STL – I can steal the ball to
  • Known as "The main man"

“PF” – Power Forward

  • Unlike the SF the Power forwards are the heaviest group of players and some of the tallest in NBA with an average height of 208cm and weight of 107kg
  • BLK – I can block
  • DRB – I can defend a rebound
  • Known as "The defender"

“C” – Center

  • These group of players are the tallest in the Nba with an average height of 210cm and weight of 106kg
  • PTS – I can score to
  • BLK – The blocking King
  • DRB – Big on defensive rebounds
  • ORB – Offensive rebound, all mine!
  • PF – I play dirty
  • TOV – I can turn things around
  • Known as "The beast"

Outliers¶

MVPs outperform the rest of the population so in essence they are outliers compared to the rest. Given that MVP data is significantly disproportionate to the rest of the players I will be hesitant to remove them if they are highlighted as outliers. Let’s use Mahalanobis distance to highlight the outliers in our data.

# Calculate Mahalanobis distance
def mahalanobis(x=None, data=None, cov=None):
    """Compute the Mahalanobis Distance between each row of x and the data  
    x    : vector or matrix of data with, say, p columns.
    data : ndarray of the distribution from which Mahalanobis distance of each observation of x is to be computed.
    cov  : covariance matrix (p x p) of the distribution. If None, will be computed from data.
    """
    x_minus_mu = x - np.mean(final_outlier)
    if not cov:
        cov = np.cov(final_outlier.values.T)
    inv_covmat = np.linalg.inv(cov)
    left_term = np.dot(x_minus_mu, inv_covmat)
    mahal = np.dot(left_term, x_minus_mu.T)
    return mahal.diagonal()

df_x = final_outlier[["PCA_1","PCA_2","mvp"]]
df_x['mahala'] = mahalanobis(x=df_x, data=final_outlier[["PCA_1","PCA_2"]])

As suspected the Mahalanobis distance highlighted outliers which are identical to the MVP points. As a result, I will not be removing the outliers or else I will have no MVP data. It is one of the Logistic Regression Assumptions that no extreme outliers are present, even though visually the outliers don’t seem to be extreme in fact they are at the end of the Mahalanobis distance spectrum. This could be something for further work on how to deal with outliers in sports when analysing high preforming Athletes as they will always outperform the population.

One of the Logistic Regression assumptions is Observation independent, meaning each the observations are independent from each other or related to each other in any way. This means we cannot use any advance statistics in the model as they are all calculated from the basic statistics, hence why we have some highly correlated variables in the correlation matrix above. So, we will go ahead and only select the basic stats.

Predicting MVP¶

For this section we will use Logistic Regression to predict an MVP player based on independent and non-correlated basic performance statistics.

Model: Logistic Regression

In [755]:
# Import Packages
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report
# Define X values for the model
X = feats[['Age','G','DRB_per','AST_per','STL_per','BLK_per','TOV_per','PF_per','PTS_per','3P_per',
           'final_won','final_lost']]
# Define Y value
y = feats['mvp']
# Set groups and split
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size = .3, random_state=25)
# Create model
LogReg = LogisticRegression()
LogReg.fit(X_train, y_train)
# Predict on unseen data
y_pred = LogReg.predict(X_test)

As we can see from our results that the model was very accurate in predicting normal players with no inaccuracies. Where the model failed was in its Recall metric for value equals “1”, which is predicting MVP players. Out of the 14 MVPs in the test data the model wasn’t able to predict one MVP correctly.

From the predictors that had the strongest influence were ‘PTS_per & ‘DRB_per’

The next steps will be to validate the results using K-fold and to further try to improve the model despite already normalising predictors, ensuring predictors were independent and removing highly correlated predictors.

K-Fold Validation:¶

In [758]:
# Import packages
from sklearn.model_selection import KFold
import scipy.stats as stats
import numpy as np

kf = KFold(n_splits=6)
foldCount = 0
for train_idxs, test_idxs in kf.split(feats):
    print("Run: ", foldCount)
    print(len(feats),len(train_idxs),len(test_idxs))
    ytrain = y.iloc[train_idxs]
    Xtrain = X.iloc[train_idxs]
    ytest = y.iloc[test_idxs]
    Xtest = X.iloc[test_idxs]
    # Create the model
    LogReg = LogisticRegression()
    LogReg.fit(Xtrain, ytrain)
    # Predict on unseen data
    y_pred = LogReg.predict(Xtest) 
    
    # Confusion matrix
    mat = confusion_matrix(ytest,y_pred)
    sns.heatmap(mat.T, square =True, annot = True, fmt = 'd', cbar= False)
    plt.xlabel('True data')
    plt.ylabel('predicted values')
    plt.show()
    # Print performance metrics
    print(classification_report(ytest, y_pred))
    foldCount += 1

But looking at our data we can see it suffered from class imbalance which can make it hard for the model to classify when there is only a small number of MVP rows to learn from. We should also remember we were unable to remove outliers which could of effected the model potentially or the fact the points in the data that were most important to us are considered outliers.
